snippet.textDisplay: I’m recommended “what if it’s us” which is a gay book about these two teens who meet in a post office but are pulled are apart by a flash mob and have to try and reunite with eachother with only knowing the others appearance and 1.5/2 names. It’s written by the authors of “Simon vs the homosapian agenda” and “they both die in the end”. It’s a really good and interesting book, the dialogue is realistic and internal monologue is pretty great. I have dyslexia and ADD/ADHD, so even though I love to read it tends to be hard for me. I used to read all the time as a kid but then my friend would make fun of me for reading so slow and it’s so hard for me to actually finish a book once I put it down. But as a generally creative person, and someone who loves to write stories, I’m trying to get over my insecurities and find how to work with my brain instead of against it.

But the names are, Book 1, The Dragonet Prophecy. Book 2, The Lost Heir. And Book 3, The Hidden Kingdom. You can get these off of Amazon if your interested. The series is about dragons by the way. Also, DON'T judge the age rating for it because if your not mature, just forget all that I just said. But if you ARE mature, you should read it. I hope you guys take this suggestion and enjoy it.

snippet.textDisplay: I loved reading books in school, i was reading 12th grade level books in 5th grade and enjoying books that nobody else liked but then they started telling me "you can get a reward for reading a book and submitting a short summary on it to a certain website" (i didn't really care to at the time) what made me start to dislike reading was when they started pressuring me to submit summarys of the books i read. The rewards were actually kinda good but thats why it ruined the fun of reading for me, and eventually it caused me to stop all together. If their overarching goal was to make me smarter by reading more then they failed miserably
